title: For Sale:  Remington Police Magnum
location: West Palm Beach/Treasure Coast, Florida, United States
postcontent:
This is NOT a Remington Express gun - this is Police Magnum, which is much more durable!

Remington Police Magnums come with a parkerized finish on an 18" barrel (as opposed to a Blued finish on an Express); feature a stronger sear spring and magazine spring; better extractor and ejector, and much more.

Shotgun has rifle sights and has been gone over completely by in-house Remington LE Certified Armorer. This shotgun goes for $650 new in the box if your are Law Enforcement.

Sold 3 this weekend - only 2 left!

$500 each.

I am not interested in trades at this time - Cash sales only please.

This is a private sale.

$15 transfer fee paid directly to FFL, or use the FFL of your preference.

Call or text REDACTED



Differences between an Express 870 and a Police Magnum 870:

The 870 Express has been an important part of Remington’s offering to the sporting market. It was designed to meet a price point in the commercial market while still providing classic 870 functionality. All of Remington’s 870’s have interchangeable parts, even if they have cosmetic differences. It is also important to note that many manufacturers use the 870 Express platform for their Police / Combat models. Without exception, every manufacturer who utilizes our 870 platform serves to upgrade their system to a more efficient, street worthy platform.

While the 870 Express is still an 870, the best pump shotgun on the market, there are some very important cosmetic and functional differences between it and the 870 Police. To our customers in Law Enforcement, Military, Corrections, and Security, whose lives depend upon the unfailing performance of Remington shotguns, the Police modifications are of paramount importance.Synopses of the variances are provided below.


870 Police shotguns go thru a special 23 station check list – ranging from visual inspection, functional testing, test firing, and final inspection.   
All Police shotguns are assembled in a “special build area” at the plant in Ilion, NY. This section is secured and serves only to build LE and Military shotguns, with the same factory personnel working at that assignment each shift.
All parts that enter the “special build area” are visually inspected by hand to ensure top quality and functionality.
Due to heavy recoil in buck and slug loads, all 870 Police guns have a longer magazine spring which ensures positive feed and function.   
A heavier sear spring is used to generate a reliable, positive trigger pull between 5 and 8 lbs.   
A heavier carrier dog spring is used to ensure when the carrier elevates the shell, it will be held there until the bolt can push it into the chamber. This ensures positive feeding when using heavier payload rounds.   
Police shotguns do not have an ISS (Integrated Safety System) which is a locking mechanism on the safety of commercial shotguns. This type of locking mechanism can cause delay to an officer who needs the weapon but does not have the appropriate key. LE shotguns have the standard, proven, cross bolt safety.   
The fore-end on the Express model is longer and not compatible with many police shotgun vehicle racks. The Police shotguns utilize the heavy duty SPEEDFEED Stocks and Fore-ends.   
The Express model will not allow for the addition of an extension tube without physical modification to the tube and barrel, which can nullify the warranty.   
The Express model has a BEAD BLAST BLUE finish while the Police models utilize Parkerization. The Express model utilizes a synthetic trigger housing while the Police models use a compressed metal housing.
The Police shotgun barrel is locked down with a “ball detent” system in conjunction with the magazine cap vs. a lesser grade “synthetic magazine spring retainer” lock down as used on the Express system.   
The receivers used in Police guns are “vibra honed” to smooth out rough finishes and remove burrs before parkerization.   
Police shotguns use machined ejectors and extractors, as opposed to powdered metal cast which are utilized on the Express models.

I bought this to add to a tactical setup that I have since switched away from. The whole thing is in very good shape, with a little scuffing, but that’s all.

title: For Sale:  1895 Winchester  30-1903 cal. RARE!
postcontent: The model 95 is a rare gun made famous by Teddy Roosevelt. The .30-1903 was adopted by the Army in 1903 to replace the aging .30 Army (.30-40 Krag) which had been adopted in 1892. Winchester first offered the model 1895 in the .30-03 cartridge in 1905. Unfortunately, the '03 cartridge became all but obsolete only a year later with the adoption by the Army of the .30-06 in 1906. (Commercial ammo for the '03 was made up until WWI.) It wasn't until 1908 that Winchester produced the 1895 in '06. This pictured gun was born in 1912. Bright bore with great rifling, 50% bluing, wood has no cracks and has great wood to metal fit, originally had a Lyman 21 sight which was removed and a rear marble was installed. I would replace marble with a Lyman 21 to bring it back to originally configuration. This gun is also more desirable because it does not come with the standard 28" barrel, but the 24".

title: For Sale/Trade:  Bushmaster AR-15 Competition Rifle
postcontent:
I’m offering for sale my Bushmaster PCWA2S 20DCM8 competition AR15 rifle.   I purchased this rifle in 2001, and estimate 200 rounds have been fired from this rifle.  Bushmaster currently sells this rifle under the model number DCM-XR Order No. 90543.  See link http://www.bushmaster.com/firearms/competition.asp   Current sale price is $1,360.39 plus tax and shipping.

If you are just looking for an AR, you do not want this rifle.  This is a specific purpose, serious competition rifle, not just a range blaster.  

This rifle is specifically designed to compete in the “Service Class” high-power rifle competition like that held at Camp Perry each year.

In keeping with the DCM (Department of Civilian Marksmanship) rules, this rifle looks like a stock M16/AR15 but includes accurizing modifications that will give you the winning edge.
Features include;
•	An A2 rear sight specially modified to accept interchangeable “micro-apeture” peeps; 0.036”, 0.040”, 0.046” and 0.052” will be included with the rifle.
•	The rear sight windage and elevation mechanisms feature ¼” MOA adjustment with each click of adjustment.
•	Competition front sight blades (0.052” and 0.062” included with the rifle) ground for optimum visual clarity.
•	A 20” extra heavy competition barrel – a full 1” diameter under the handguard.  Precision button rifled in a 1 x 8” right hand twist with an 11 crowned competition muzzle.  The barrel is machined from Chrome-Moly Vanadium steel and hardened to Rockwell C26 to 32.  This barrel is superior to stainless or chrome lined.
•	The upper receiver is matched to both the bolt and the lower.
•	The lower receiver houses a finely honed competition two-stage trigger set for 3.5lb 1st Stage and a 1lb letoff (2nd Stage).
•	The forearm stock/grip is ‘free floating’, not attached to the barrel, but directly to the receiver.  The sling swivel is attached to the leading edge of the stock, so likewise it is attached to the receiver and can not influence any barrel deflection from your grip or wrapping the sling.
•	The buttstock has a tune-able and/or removeable 3lb lead insert to allow you to tune the rifle to achieve the balance you would like.  I have not altered this weight.

This is a pro competition rifle, not just a range blaster.  If you’re just looking for an AR, you do not want this rifle.  Mostly because it weighs 13.5lbs and is a chore to drag around, but if you want to get into high-power rifle competition shooting service class than this is your ticket.
